Looking at the mutation, the change is:
- Original: `if (this._waitForDrain) break;`
- Mutated: `if (true) break;`

This means in the mutated code, the `_flush()` loop will always break after writing the first key, whereas in the original code it only breaks when `_waitForDrain` is true (i.e., when the write stream's buffer is full).

The key behavioral difference: when multiple keys are queued for writing, the original code will write all of them in one flush (unless backpressure occurs), while the mutated code will only write one key per flush call.

I need to test that when multiple keys are set, they all get persisted correctly. The test should verify that multiple callbacks are called when multiple keys are set simultaneously.

